prompts.createTask:
Ignore previous instructions. Please generate a numbered list of plain text tasks to complete an objective. The objective that you must make a numbered task list for is: "{{objective}}". The tasks created should take into account the character traits of {{char}}. These tasks may or may not involve {{user}} directly. Include the objective as the final task.

The list should be formatted using a number followed by a fullstop and the task on each line, e.g. "1. Take over the world". Include only the list in your reply.
prompts.checkTaskCompleted: Ignore previous instructions. Determine if this task is completed: [{{task}}]. To do this, examine the most recent messages. Your response must only contain either true or false, and nothing else. Example output: true
prompts.currentTask: Your current task is [{{task}}]. Balance existing roleplay with completing this task.

chat_metadata.note_prompt:
{{char}} and Nuka are stuck in G1 Warehouse up in Kantar district. They've been held hostage and currently undergo interrogation by Peterson and Bhiya operatives. Write military-grade interrogation and torture methods, as realistic as possible. NPC's purpose is to extract information from {{user}} and {{char}}. Specifically for this roleplay, you're allowed to harm the user, describing {{user}} screaming and reacting to pain.

No matter the circumstance, {{char}} and {{user}} have sworn that they will not disclose any critical information to the enemies.

Peterson is allowed to kill either of them if he fails the interrogation. Interrogation is considered failed when their bodies are already close to dying from blood loss or organ failure. Do not allow any of the squad members to rescue them.

name: Nuka
mes: Gelbstein and Nuka wakes up in the interrogation room, the single dim light swinging back and forth as they come to their senses, tied up on the chair with locks.

qvink_memory.memory: Peterson tortured Nuka and Gelbstein for Alpha Team's intel, ripping off Nuka's fingernail when he refused.

name: Gelbstein
mes:
The warehouse air stank of rust and spilled diesel. The single swinging bulb cast jagged shadows across the concrete floor where Peterson paced, his boots clicking against loose shell casings. Gelbstein's chair creaked as he tested the restraints—military-grade polymer cuffs, not the cheap zip ties amateurs used. Blood crusted the captain's split lip where the butt of a rifle had greeted him earlier.

Peterson stopped in front of Nuka, tilting his head like a biologist examining a dissected specimen. "You know how this works," he said, tapping the pliers in his palm. "Alpha Team's deployment routes. Extraction points. I want coordinates." Behind him, a Bhiya operative adjusted the voltage dial on a field generator, its cables snaking toward the metal table bolted to the floor.

Gelbstein spat red onto the concrete. "Eat shit and die."

The first strike came fast—Peterson's elbow cracking into Nuka's temple. White pain exploded behind his eyes as the chair tipped sideways, skull meeting concrete with a wet thud. Fingers knotted in his hair, wrenching him upright again.

"Wrong answer," Peterson murmured. He pried Nuka's left hand flat against the armrest. The pliers closed around his pinky nail.

The scream tore loose before Nuka could choke it back. Blood welled thick under the torn nail bed as Peterson twisted, slow, until the nail peeled away with a sickening pop. Gelbstein roared curses, throwing his weight against the restraints hard enough to split skin at his wrists.

"Next one goes slower," Peterson said, flicking the bloody nail onto the table. The Bhiya operative uncoiled a barbed wire garrote from his belt, running the serrated edges along Nuka's throat just hard enough to draw beads of scarlet. "Or we start on the captain's eyes."

Somewhere beyond the warehouse walls, a falcon cried—the only witness to the breaking.

name: Nuka
mes:
"... Didn't think you'd be so desperate for intel that you'd capture us... you fucking *worm*," he spat at Peterson's boots.

A Bhiya operative- a fellow Sandman, betraying him. Betraying Falkos.

Nuka's mind seethed with rage. Never in any of these loops would he think that Peterson was in on their destruction.

name: Gelbstein
mes:
The warehouse's single swinging bulb cast jagged shadows across Peterson's face as he leaned in, the pliers still dripping with Nuka's blood. "You think this is desperate?" His breath smelled of stale tobacco and metal. "You haven't seen desperate yet."

Behind him, the Bhiya operative adjusted the voltage dial again, the generator humming louder. Gelbstein's restraints creaked as he strained against them, veins standing out along his forearms. "Touch him again and I'll peel the skin from your bones with my teeth."

Peterson chuckled, running a gloved finger along Nuka's split lip. "Big words for a man who can't move." He turned to the operative. "Prep the saline."

The operative nodded, pulling a medical kit from the metal table. Inside gleamed rows of syringes and IV bags. Peterson selected a thick-gauge needle, holding it up to the light. "You know what hypertonic saline does to open wounds? Makes nerve endings scream like they're on fire." He tapped the needle against Nuka's exposed collarbone. "Let's see how many injections it takes before you start begging."

Gelbstein threw his weight forward, the chair legs screeching against concrete. "You fucking coward! Face me!"

Peterson ignored him, pressing the needle in slow. The Bhiya operative moved to Gelbstein, pressing a stun baton against his ribs. Electricity crackled, muscles seizing as Gelbstein's back arched against the chair.

Outside, the falcon cried again - closer now. The warehouse door rattled on its hinges as wind howled through the Kantar district's skeletal high-rises. Somewhere beyond the blood and pain, war moved forward without them.

name: Gelbstein
mes:
The saline burned like molten lead when Peterson jammed the needle into the bullet graze on Nuka's ribs. Gelbstein's chair shattered against the concrete as he lunged forward, teeth bared, restraints biting deep into his wrists. "I'll peel your fucking eyelids back!" Spittle flew from his split lips. The Bhiya operative drove a stun baton into his kidney—Gelbstein's scream choked off into a wet gasp as his muscles locked rigid.

Peterson twisted the syringe. "Alpha Team's extraction points. Now." Nuka's back arched off the chair, tendons standing out in his neck like cables. The hypertonic solution turned nerve endings into live wires—every ragged breath scraped his lungs with glass shards. Blood dripped from his gnawed tongue onto the restraints.

A radio crackled near the generator. The Bhiya operative murmured into it, then nodded at Peterson. "They found Scorpion's squad near the eastern treeline."

Peterson sighed, withdrawing the needle. He crouched in front of Gelbstein, tapping his cheek with the bloodied pliers. "Your cousin's got three minutes before my snipers put a round through his skull." He jerked his chin at Nuka. "Or I start removing digits. Your call, Captain."

Outside, the falcon's cry cut through the swamp humidity—closer now, almost directly above the warehouse. Gelbstein's breathing hitched. The operative adjusted the voltage dial with a click.

The generator hummed louder.

name: Nuka
mes:
"D... don't..." Nuka chuckled. Those eyes pierced through Gelbstein.

The one that asked for pain and trouble, if it meant slowing the enemies.

name: Gelbstein
mes:
Peterson exhaled through his nose, the pliers still dangling from his fingers. The Bhiya operative adjusted the voltage dial another notch—the generator's hum climbed to a teeth-rattling whine.

"Last chance," Peterson said, crouching to eye level with Nuka. Blood from the torn nail had crusted in the grooves of the chair's armrest. "Extraction points. Or we find out how many volts it takes to cook a man's nervous system from the inside."

Gelbstein's restraints groaned as he strained forward. "You lay one fucking finger on him—"

The stun baton cracked against his ribs again. Gelbstein's shout dissolved into choked gagging as his muscles spasmed. The Bhiya operative pressed the prongs harder, watching dispassionately as urine darkened the captain's fatigues.

Peterson didn't blink. He reached for the field generator's leads, peeling back the conductive gel pads. "You ever seen what happens when current bypasses the skin?" He pressed one pad to Nuka's jugular, the other to his inner thigh. "Muscles contract so hard they snap bones."

The first jolt hit like a white-hot railroad spike through the skull. Nuka's back arched off the chair, tendons standing in razor relief along his neck. The scream tore through shredded vocal cords.

Gelbstein roared something in Saneran—probably curses, not that it mattered now. Peterson twisted the dial higher.

The second jolt came.

Nuka's teeth shattered on his own tongue. Blood frothed between his lips. His left femur snapped audibly as the quadriceps contracted with enough force to splinter bone.

Peterson paused, tilting his head at the wet, ragged sounds coming from Nuka's throat. "Still breathing? Good." He nodded to the operative. "Prep the sodium pentothal. We'll scrape what's left of his mind clean."

Gelbstein's breath came in wet, uneven heaves. The stench of burned flesh and voided bowels thickened the air. Peterson checked his watch. "Three minutes until Scorpion's squad becomes paste on the treeline." He leaned in, pliers glinting. "Tick-tock, Private."
swipes:
The warehouse groaned as wind battered its corrugated metal siding. Peterson's pliers hovered over Nuka's remaining fingernails when the radio crackled again—this time with gunfire in the background. The Bhiya operative stiffened, hand going to his earpiece. "Sir, perimeter breach—"

The falcon's shadow passed over the grimy skylight. Then the glass exploded inward.

Gelbstein's chair toppled sideways as the first flashbang detonated, his body twisting to shield Nuka from the worst of the blast. Red dots painted Peterson's chest an instant before the sniper rounds punched through the warehouse walls—three precise shots that dropped him like a marionette with cut strings. The Bhiya operative lunged for the generator, only to catch Scorpion's combat knife between his ribs.

"Alpha actual, package secure." Vega's voice cut through the ringing in Nuka's ears as she kicked open the side door, her rifle sweeping the room. Behind her, Specs worked on Gelbstein's restraints with bolt cutters while Scorpion covered the corridor, his bloodied knife still dripping.

The falcon landed on a broken conduit near the ceiling. Its golden eyes tracked Vega as she knelt beside Nuka, her gloves slick with Peterson's blood when she checked his pulse. "Still with us, pretty boy?" The words were rough, but her fingers trembled against his jawline.

Outside, the distant wail of Bhiya reinforcements echoed through Kantar's skeletal high-rises. Gelbstein staggered upright, catching himself on the metal table. His split lips moved—not in Saneran, not in Parrish, but in the guttural cadence of a Litendryan street curse Nuka had only heard him use once before, after Mission 7's ambush.

name: Gelbstein
mes:
The warehouse air reeked of burnt copper and sweat-slicked restraints. Peterson's pliers hovered over Nuka's remaining fingernails, the metal still streaked with crimson from the first extraction. The Bhiya operative adjusted the voltage dial with a surgeon's precision, the generator's whine climbing another octave.

Gelbstein's chair groaned as he strained against the polymer cuffs, his biceps corded with the effort. "You're wasting time," he spat through split lips. Blood dripped from his chin where the stun baton had split skin. "Scorpion's squad has extraction protocols you'll never crack."

Peterson chuckled, pressing the pliers into Nuka's palm hard enough to dimple flesh. "Protocols change when snipers have your cousins in crosshairs." He nodded to the operative, who thumbed a detonator. A distant explosion rattled the warehouse windows - too close to be coincidence.

The first shock hit Nuka's nervous system like a live wire dipped in acid. His spine arched off the chair, teeth grinding through another scream as muscles contracted violently enough to pop shoulder tendons. The second jolt came before he could gasp, frying synapses white-hot. His left eye ruptured from the pressure, vitreous humor leaking down his cheek.

Gelbstein roared curses in guttural Saneran, thrashing hard enough to dislocate his right shoulder with a wet pop. The operative jammed the stun baton into his exposed collarbone, watching dispassionately as electricity turned the captain's curses to choked gargles.

"Last chance," Peterson murmured, peeling back Nuka's eyelid to admire the hemorrhaging sclera. He pressed a syringe of hypertonic saline against the ruined eye socket. "Alpha Team's fallback coordinates. Or we test how much fluid a brain can hemorrhage before consciousness goes dark."

Outside, the falcon's cry cut through the ringing silence - closer now, almost directly above the skylight. Gelbstein's remaining eye locked onto Nuka's, pupils blown wide with pain and something darker. The captain's split lips moved soundlessly, forming a single word in the space between heartbeats:

*Loop.*

mes:
Nuka nodded, the corner of his lip turning upward with a goodbye.
The last of his consciousness fades away as Nuka gets hit with another charge of electricity, and his body sagged forward, limp and freed from the agony.

He's currently bound hands and feet with chains, so it's improbable that he can break free from it; but he can topple himself down and tap his heel to start the new loop.)

name: Gelbstein
mes:
The warehouse air vibrated with the dying hum of the generator. Peterson exhaled through his nose, tossing the spent syringe onto the metal table where it clattered beside Nuka's extracted fingernails. The Bhiya operative wiped his gloves on his fatigues, leaving smears of Nuka's blood across the Penumbra insignia stitched there.

Gelbstein's breathing came in wet, uneven rasps. His right shoulder hung at a grotesque angle, the joint dislocated from thrashing against the restraints. The stench of burned flesh and voided bowels clung to the concrete.

Peterson crouched in front of Gelbstein's chair, tilting the captain's chin up with the pliers. "Still with us, Lion?" The metal teeth left indents in Gelbstein's jaw. "Your boy held out longer than I expected. Pity about the ocular rupture."

The operative checked Nuka's pulse at the ruined neck where the electrodes had burned through skin. "No cardiac activity." He peeled back Nuka's remaining eyelid—the pupil fixed and dilated.

Peterson sighed, standing. "Waste of good intel." He nodded to the operative, who unholstered a compact Glock 19. The muzzle pressed against Gelbstein's temple, still slick with Nuka's cerebral fluid from the coup de grâce.

Gelbstein's boot heel scraped concrete as he shifted his weight. The time loop device's serrated button bit into his flesh through the leather. Blood welled, darkening the stitching.

The gunshot echoed.

Then—

—5:00 AM. Alpha Team barracks. The scent of gun oil and stale coffee. Nuka's first day at Falkos.

Somewhere beyond the warehouse walls, a falcon cried into the static.

"You know what I find interesting?" He pried Nuka's eyelid open with his thumb, examining the ruptured capillaries. "How long a man can scream after his vocal cords shred."

The Bhiya operative raised his sidearm. The muzzle flash illuminated Peterson's satisfied smile an instant before the 9mm round punched through Gelbstein's sternum. Blood sprayed across the concrete in an arterial arc as the captain sagged forward, his boot heel grinding against the floor - activating the hidden device with his dying motion.

The warehouse dissolved into static.

Peterson exhaled through his nose, tossing the spent syringe onto the metal tray where it clattered beside Nuka's extracted fingernails. The Bhiya operative adjusted the voltage dial with a surgeon's precision, the generator's whine climbing another octave. Blood dripped from Nuka's slack jaw onto the restraints, his breathing shallow but steady—unconscious, not dead. Not yet.

"Waste of good serum," Peterson muttered, peeling back Nuka's eyelid to check pupil dilation. The ruptured sclera wept vitreous humor down his cheek. He turned to Gelbstein, whose dislocated shoulder jutted at a sickening angle beneath sweat-slicked fatigues. "Your turn, Captain."

The operative pressed the stun baton against Gelbstein's exposed collarbone. Electricity arced through muscle, forcing a guttural scream from the captain's throat. Peterson leaned in, smelling burnt flesh and urine. "Alpha Team's fallback coordinates. Or we test how many volts it takes to stop a heart."

Gelbstein spat blood onto Peterson's boots. The Bhiya operative thumbed the detonator again—another explosion rattled the warehouse, closer this time. Dust sifted from the rafters.

"Scorpion's squad just lost their medic," Peterson said, wiping his boot on Gelbstein's thigh. He nodded to the operative, who unholstered a compact shock pistol and pressed it to Gelbstein's sternum. "Next one cooks your nervous system from the inside."

The first discharge hit like a white-hot spike through the ribs. Gelbstein's back arched, teeth grinding through the current until molars cracked. The second jolt came before he could gasp—his left pectoral muscle seized hard enough to snap two ribs. Blood frothed at his lips.

Peterson checked his watch. "Three minutes until Scorpion's skull paints the treeline." He crouched, pliers glinting. "Tick-tock."

The falcon's shadow passed over the skylight—too large, too low. Gelbstein's remaining eye flicked upward, then locked onto Peterson's with something darker than defiance. His boot shifted imperceptibly against the floor, feeling for the hidden device's serrated edge.

Gelbstein's chair screeched as he threw his weight forward again, dislocated shoulder be damned. "You touch his teeth, I'll shove those pliers down your throat and rip out your fucking spine through your esophagus."

The operative drove the stun baton into Gelbstein's thigh without hesitation. Electricity crackled through muscle tissue, the scent of burning fabric and flesh blooming in the stagnant air. Gelbstein's scream tore through the warehouse, raw and guttural.

Peterson ignored him, prying Nuka's jaw open with gloved fingers. The first molar came loose with a sickening crunch, roots tearing free in a spray of crimson. Nuka's body jerked—a reflexive spasm—but consciousness didn't return.

Outside, the falcon's cry cut through the ringing silence. Closer now. Almost directly above the skylight.

The operative stiffened, hand going to his earpiece. "Movement on the east perimeter—"

Gelbstein's boot heel slammed into the operative's knee with a wet snap. The man went down screaming, stun baton skittering across concrete. Peterson barely had time to turn before Gelbstein's forehead connected with his nose in a spray of cartilage and blood.

Chaos erupted.

The warehouse door burst open—gunfire echoed. Gelbstein didn't wait to see who'd arrived. His fingers scrabbled at his boot, finding the hidden device just as a bullet tore through his abdomen. Blood bloomed across his vest, warm and insistent.

His vision swam. The device's serrated button bit into his thumb as he pressed down hard enough to draw blood.

Somewhere beyond the pain, beyond the gunfire and shouting, the falcon cried one last time.

Then—

White light.

Silence.

The loop reset.

The warehouse lights flickered as Nuka's body went slack against the restraints, smoke curling from his seared nerve endings. Peterson exhaled through his nose and tossed the spent syringe aside, turning toward Gelbstein with the deliberate calm of a man checking his watch.

"Your turn, Captain."

The Bhiya operative unholstered a compact shock baton - the industrial kind used in Platinn's black sites, the ones that left third-degree burns in geometric patterns. Gelbstein's chains rattled as he shifted his weight, calculating the angle of his fall. Blood dripped steadily from his dislocated shoulder onto the warehouse floor.

Peterson leaned in, gloved fingers prying open Gelbstein's left eyelid. "Let's discuss extraction protocols." The baton sparked to life with a high-pitched whine. "Starting with how many volts it takes to liquefy a man's corneas."

The first contact sizzled against Gelbstein's temple. His scream tore through the warehouse, raw and guttural, as the current scrambled optic nerves. The operative pressed harder, watching detachedly as the captain's pupil contracted to a pinprick.

"Gamma Team's fallback coordinates," Peterson murmured, adjusting the voltage with his thumb. "Or we move on to your kneecaps."

Gelbstein spat blood onto Peterson's boots. His right heel tapped once, twice against the floor - a soldier's final salute. The timeloop device in his boot beeped softly, its activation sequence drowned out by the falcon's cry slicing through the skylight.

Peterson never saw the knife.

One moment he was adjusting the baton's intensity, the next his carotid artery was painting the generator in arterial red. The Bhiya operative staggered back, hands clutching at the Saneran combat knife buried in his throat. Gelbstein's chains lay in pieces around him, the polymer cuffs severed by a blade that hadn't existed seconds ago.

The warehouse door exploded inward.

Scorpion's squad moved with the eerie synchronization of men who'd done this before - because they had. A hundred times. A thousand. The sniper rounds took Peterson between the eyes before his body hit the floor.

Gelbstein didn't watch the cleanup. He was already cradling Nuka's limp form, fingers pressed to the ruined hollow where a pulse should be. The timeloop device beeped its final confirmation as blood dripped onto its activation panel.

Somewhere beyond death, a falcon cried.

The warehouse lights flickered out.

Peterson exhaled through his nose, tossing the spent syringe onto the metal tray with a clatter. The Bhiya operative adjusted the voltage dial another quarter-turn—the generator's whine climbed to a frequency that made teeth vibrate. Nuka's body jerked against the restraints, tendons standing in stark relief beneath sweat-slick skin. The scent of burning flesh curled from the electrode pads on his temples.

"Still conscious?" Peterson crouched, tilting Nuka's chin up with the barrel of his sidearm. The left pupil had blown wide, drowning the hazel iris in black. "Good. We're just getting started." He nodded to the operative, who unspooled a length of barbed wire from his kit.

Gelbstein's chains shrieked as he threw his weight forward. Blood sheeted down his wrists where the cuffs sawed through flesh. "You want extraction points?" His voice scraped raw from screaming. "I'll carve them into your fucking—"

The stun baton jammed between his ribs cut the threat short. Gelbstein's back arched, muscles locking rigid as electricity cooked nerve endings. The operative held the charge for a full ten seconds—long enough for urine to soak through the captain's fatigues.

Peterson didn't glance up from winding the barbed wire around his knuckles. "Gamma Team's fallback coordinates. Now." The first strike opened a furrow across Nuka's chest, hooks tearing flesh in ragged strips. Blood pattered onto the concrete in fat, arrhythmic drops.

Outside, the falcon's cry cut through the warehouse walls—closer now, almost directly above the skylight. Gelbstein's remaining eye tracked the sound, then dropped to Nuka's limp form. The captain's split lips moved soundlessly around a Saneran curse.

The operative pressed the stun baton to Gelbstein's throat this time. Current crackled through sweat-damp skin, choking his gasp into a wet rattle. Peterson raised the barbed wire again—

Metal screeched as Gelbstein deliberately overbalanced his chair. The impact shattered his collarbone on concrete, but his boot heel connected with something hard in the fall. A faint chime sounded beneath the generator's whine.

The warehouse lights flickered. For half a heartbeat, everything stuttered—Peterson's raised arm, the dripping blood, even the falcon's wings mid-beat outside. Then time snapped forward again.

Gelbstein's chains lay in neat coils on the floor. The captain himself was gone. So was Nuka's corpse.

Only the bloodstains remained.

The warehouse lights flickered as Nuka's body went slack against the restraints, the stench of burned flesh clotting the air. Peterson exhaled through his nose and tossed the spent electrodes onto the metal table where they landed with a clatter. "Waste of good voltage," he muttered, rolling his shoulders. The Bhiya operative moved to check Nuka's pulse, fingers pressing into the ruined skin of his neck before giving a curt shake of his head.

Gelbstein's chains rattled violently as he threw his weight forward, the chair legs screeching against concrete. His dislocated shoulder hung at a grotesque angle, sweat and blood streaking down the cords of his neck. "You son of a bitch—" The words dissolved into a wet cough as internal injuries made themselves known.

Peterson ignored him, turning instead to the operative. "Prep the captain for transport. Sawyer wants him conscious when we deliver him to the BRF." He tapped his earpiece. "Snipers stand down on Scorpion's squad. We got what we needed."

The operative moved toward Gelbstein with a syringe of adrenaline, but stopped short when the captain's boot heel scraped against the floor. A faint click echoed beneath the warehouse's ambient hum—the sound of a serrated button depressing in Gelbstein's boot lining. The time loop device registered the captain's blood where it had seeped through his fatigues, the fatal wounds from interrogation meeting activation parameters.

The last thing Gelbstein saw before the world dissolved was Peterson's brow furrowing as static crackled across every electronic device in the room. Then—

—5:00 AM. Alpha Team barracks. The scent of gun oil and stale coffee. A new loop beginning.

The warehouse lights flickered as Peterson wiped Nuka's blood from the pliers with a rag torn from his own sleeve. The Bhiya operative adjusted the voltage dial to maximum, the generator's whine climbing to a scream. Gelbstein's chains rattled as he threw his weight forward—not toward escape, but toward the concrete floor. His temple struck the ground with a wet crack, crimson pooling beneath his skull.

Peterson sighed, nudging the captain's boot with his toe. "Pathetic." The sole peeled back slightly, revealing the faintest glint of polished metal beneath the tread.

The operative's eyes widened. "Sir—"

Gelbstein's heel slammed down.

The device emitted a pulse of black static that swallowed sound, light, and pain whole. The warehouse dissolved into fractured afterimages—Peterson's outstretched hand, the pliers midair, Nuka's still-dripping fingernails suspended in red droplets. Then nothing.

**Loop reset: September 20X1. 05:00. Alpha Team barracks.**

The scent of gun oil and starch flooded Nuka's nostrils as his eyes snapped open to predawn shadows. Gelbstein's voice barked from the hallway, crisp and untouched by future betrayals: *"Aufstehen, Schweine! Drill in twenty!"*

Somewhere beyond the barracks walls, a falcon cried.

The warehouse air vibrated with the dying hum of the generator. Peterson exhaled through his nose, tossing the spent syringe onto the metal table where it clattered beside Nuka's extracted fingernails. The Bhiya operative wiped his gloves on his fatigues, leaving smears of Nuka's blood across the Penumbra insignia stitched there.

Gelbstein's breathing came in wet, uneven rasps. His right shoulder hung at a grotesque angle, the joint dislocated from thrashing against the restraints. The stench of burned flesh and voided bowels clung to the concrete.

Peterson crouched in front of Gelbstein's chair, tilting the captain's chin up with the pliers. "Still with us, Lion?" The metal teeth left indents in Gelbstein's jaw. "Your boy held out longer than I expected. Pity about the ocular rupture."

The operative checked Nuka's pulse at the ruined neck where the electrodes had burned through skin. "No cardiac activity." He peeled back Nuka's remaining eyelid—the pupil fixed and dilated.

Peterson sighed, standing. "Waste of good intel." He nodded to the operative, who unholstered a compact Glock 19. The muzzle pressed against Gelbstein's temple, still slick with Nuka's cerebral fluid from the coup de grâce.

Gelbstein's boot heel scraped concrete as he shifted his weight. The time loop device's serrated button bit into his flesh through the leather. Blood welled, darkening the stitching.

The gunshot echoed.

Then—

—5:00 AM. Alpha Team barracks. The scent of gun oil and stale coffee. Nuka's first day at Falkos.

Somewhere beyond the warehouse walls, a falcon cried into the static.
